# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bacteriophage
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Bacteria of this genus lack flagella but exhibit twitching or swarming motility, likely mediated by type IV pili.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Motility in *A. baumannii* may also be due to the excretion of exopolysaccharide, creating a film of high-molecular-weight sugar chains behind the bacterium to move forward.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Clinical microbiologists typically differentiate members of the genus *Acinetobacter* from other Moraxellaceae by performing an oxidase test, as *Acinetobacter* spp. are the only members of the Moraxellaceae to lack cytochrome c oxidases.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] *A. baumannii* is strictly aerobic, meaning it needs oxygen to grow.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Baumannii* is able to survive in varying levels of oxygen, including no oxygen, by entering a dormant state.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Colloquially, *A. baumannii* is referred to as "**Iraqibacter**" due to its seemingly sudden emergence in military treatment facilities during the Iraq War.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] It has continued to be an issue for veterans and soldiers who served in Iraq and Afghanistan.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Multidrug-resistant *A. baumannii* has spread to civilian hospitals in part due to the transport of infected soldiers through multiple medical facilities.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] During the COVID-19 pandemic, coinfection with *A. baumannii* secondary to SARS-CoV-2 infections has been reported multiple times in medical publications.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Adhesion can be a critical determinant of virulence for bacteria.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] The ability to attach to host cells allows bacteria to interact with them in various ways, whether by type III secretion system or simply by holding on against the prevailing movement of fluids.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Outer membrane protein A (OmpA) has been shown to be involved in the adherence of *A. baumannii* to epithelial cells.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] This allows the bacteria to invade the cells through the zipper mechanism.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] The protein was also shown to localize to the mitochondria of epithelial cells.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] OmpA attachment to mitochondria induces it leading to swelling of mitochondria.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] This releases cytochrome c, which causes formation of apoptosome.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] This leads to the apoptosis of the cell.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Mechanisms of antibiotic resistance can be categorized into three groups.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] First, resistance can be achieved by reducing membrane permeability or increasing efflux of the antibiotic and thus preventing access to the target.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Second, bacteria can protect the antibiotic target through genetic mutation or post-translational modification.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Third, antibiotics can be directly inactivated by hydrolysis or modification.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] One of the most important weapons in the armoury of *Acinetobacter* is its impressive genetic plasticity, facilitating rapid genetic mutations and rearrangements as well as integration of foreign determinants carried by mobile genetic elements.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Of these, insertion sequences are considered one of the key forces shaping bacterial genomes and ultimately evolution.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Pathogenicity islands, relatively common genetic structures in bacterial pathogens, are composed of two or more adjacent genes that increase a pathogen's virulence.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] They may contain genes that encode toxins, coagulate blood, or as in this case, allow the bacteria to resist antibiotics.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] AbaR-type resistance islands are typical of drug-resistant *A. baumannii*, and different variations may be present in a given strain.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Each consists of a transposon backbone of about 16.3 Kb that facilitates horizontal gene transfer.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] This makes horizontal gene transfer of this and similar pathogenicity islands more likely because, when genetic material is taken up by a new bacterium, the transposons allow the pathogenicity island to integrate into the new microorganism's genome.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] In this case, it would grant the new microorganism the potential to resist certain antibiotics.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Antibiotic resistance genes are commonly transferred between Gram-negative bacteria through plasmids via conjugation, which accelerates the appearance of new resistant strains.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] AbaR's contain several genes for antibiotic resistance, all flanked by insertion sequences.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Conjugation experiments demonstrated that the *blaOXA-23*, *blaPER-1*, and *aphA6* genes could be successfully transferred between the clinical and the environmental isolates via the plasmid group GR6 or class 1 integrons through in vitro conjugation.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] In collaboration with some other genes, they provide resistance to aminoglycosides, aminocyclitols, tetracycline, and chloramphenicol.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Efflux pumps are protein machines that use energy to pump antibiotics and other small molecules that get into the bacterial cytoplasm and the periplasmic space out of the cell.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] By constantly pumping antibiotics out of the cell, bacteria can increase the concentration of a given antibiotic required to kill them or inhibit their growth when the target of the antibiotic is inside the bacterium.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] *A. baumannii* is known to have two major efflux pumps which decrease its susceptibility to antimicrobials.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] The first, AdeB, has been shown to be responsible for aminoglycoside resistance.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] The second, AdeDE, is responsible for efflux of a wide range of substrates, including tetracycline, chloramphenicol, and various carbapenems.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Many other efflux pumps have been implicated in *A. baumannii* resistant strains.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Bacterial small RNAs are noncoding RNAs that regulate various cellular processes.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Three sRNAs, AbsR11, AbsR25, and AbsR28, have been experimentally validated in the MTCC 1425 (ATCC15308) strain, which is a (multidrug-resistant) strain showing resistance to 12 antibiotics.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] AbsR25 sRNA could play a role in the efflux pump regulation and drug resistance.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] The formation of biofilm involves cell attachment, a fundamental process typically triggered by environmental metabolites.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] *A. baumannii* is able to use vanillic acid as its sole carbon source, like its close relative *A. baylyi*.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] This metabolic pathway is regulated by transcriptional repressor VanR.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] When vanillic acid enters the cell through VanP and VanK porins it binds to the VanR regulator, which is usually bound to P*vanABKP* and P*csu* promoters.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] This binding causes repression of P*vanABKP* and P*csu* promoters, which leads to increased expression of VanP and VanK porins in the cell membrane and increased expression of Csu pili.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] The increased expression of Csu pili results a high biofilm formation phenotype of *A. baumannii*.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Recent computational studies using genome-scale metabolic models (such as iCN718) have examined how *Acinetobacter baumannii* adapts to host environments.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Graph-based analyses of metabolic networks indicate that metabolite accessibility differs between laboratory and infection-like conditions, including modeled wound and lung infection site environments.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Research and computational iterations suggest the membrane biosynthesis pathways and phosphate-dependent processes become more constrained during infection, highlighting potential environment-specific metabolic vulnerabilities.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Symptoms of *A. baumannii* infections are often indistinguishable from other opportunistic infections caused by other opportunistic bacteria - including *Klebsiella pneumoniae* and *Streptococcus pneumoniae*.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] In some cases, *A. baumannii* may present no infection or symptoms, as with colonizing an open wound or tracheostomy site.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Because most infections are now resistant to multiple drugs, determining what susceptibilities the particular strain has is necessary for treatment to be successful.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Traditionally, infections were treated with imipenem or meropenem, but a steady rise in carbapenem-resistant *A. baumannii* has been noted.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Consequently, treatment methods often fall back on polymyxins, particularly colistin although tetracyclines have shown promise in MDR *A. baumannii*.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Colistin is considered a drug of last resort because it often causes kidney damage, among other side effects.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Prevention methods in hospitals focus on increased hand-washing and more diligent sterilization procedures.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] An *A. baumannii* infection was recently treated using phage therapy.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Phages are viruses that attack bacteria, and have also been demonstrated to resensitize *A. baumannii* to antibiotics it normally resists.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Scientists at MIT, Harvard's Broad Institute and MIT's CSAIL found a compound named halicin using deep learning that can effectively kill *A. baumannii*.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] The candidate drug abaucin has narrow-spectrum effectiveness.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Zosurabalpin kills *A. baumannii,* is effective in animal models, and is currently in Phase I clinical trials.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] American and other western soldiers in Iraq and Afghanistan were at risk of traumatic injury due to gunfire and improvised explosive devices.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Previously, infection was thought to occur due to contamination with *A. baumannii* at the time of injury.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Injured soldiers were first taken to level-I facilities, where they were stabilized.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Depending on the severity of the injury, the soldiers might then be transferred to a level-II facility, which consists of a forward surgical team, for additional stabilization.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Depending on the logistics of the locality, the injured soldiers might be transfer between these facilities several times before finally being taken to a major hospital within the combat zone (level III).
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Generally after 1–3 days, when the patients were stabilized, they were transferred by air to a regional facility (level IV) for additional treatment.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] For soldiers serving in Iraq or Afghanistan, this was typically Landstuhl Regional Medical Center in Germany.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Finally, the injured soldiers were transferred to hospitals in their home country for rehabilitation and additional treatment.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] This repeated exposure to many different medical environments seems to be the reason *A. baumannii* infections have become increasingly common.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Multidrug-resistant *A. baumannii* is a major factor in complicating the treatment and rehabilitation of injured soldiers, and has led to additional deaths.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Being referred to as an opportunistic infection, *A. baumannii* infections are highly prevalent in hospital settings.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] The importation of *A. baumannii* and subsequent presence in hospitals has been well documented.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] *A. baumannii* is usually introduced into a hospital by a colonized patient.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Due to its ability to survive on artificial surfaces and resist desiccation, it can remain and possibly infect new patients for some time.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] *A baumannii* growth is suspected to be favored in hospital settings due to the constant use of antibiotics by patients in the hospital.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] Acinetobacter can be spread by person-to-person contact or contact with contaminated surfaces.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] *Acinetobacter* can enter through open wounds, catheters and breathing tubes.
[src:bacteriophage/a-baumannii] In a study of European intensive care units in 2009, *A. baumannii* was found to be responsible for 19.1% of ventilator-associated pneumonia cases.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] In ecology, **abiotic components** or **abiotic factors** are non-living chemical and physical parts of the environment that affect living organisms and the functioning of ecosystems.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors and the phenomena associated with them underpin biology as a whole.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] They affect a wide range of species, across all forms of environmental conditions, such as marine or terrestrial animals.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] Humans can make or change abiotic factors in a species' environment.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] For instance, fertilizers can affect a snail's habitat, or the greenhouse gases which humans utilize can change marine pH levels.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] Abiotic components include physical conditions and non-living resources that affect living organisms in terms of growth, maintenance, and reproduction.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] Resources are distinguished as substances or objects in the environment required by one organism and consumed or otherwise made unavailable for use by other organisms.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] Component degradation of a substance occurs by chemical or physical processes, e.g. hydrolysis.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] All non-living components of an ecosystem, such as atmospheric conditions and water resources, are called abiotic components.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] In biology, abiotic factors can include water, light, radiation, temperature, humidity, atmosphere, acidity, salinity, precipitation, altitude, minerals, tides, rain, dissolved oxygen nutrients, and soil.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] The macroscopic climate often influences each of the above.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] Pressure and sound waves may also be considered in the context of marine or sub-terrestrial environments.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors in ocean environments also include aerial exposure, substrate, water clarity, solar energy and tides.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] Consider the differences in the mechanics of C3, C4, and CAM plants in regulating the influx of carbon dioxide to the Calvin-Benson Cycle in relation to their abiotic stressors.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] C3 plants have no mechanisms to manage photorespiration, whereas C4 and CAM plants utilize a separate PEP carboxylase enzyme to prevent photorespiration, thus increasing the yield of photosynthesis processes in certain high energy environments.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] Many Archea require very high temperatures, pressures, or unusual concentrations of chemical substances such as sulfur; this is due to their specialization into extreme conditions.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] In addition, fungi have also evolved to survive at the temperature, the humidity, and stability of their environment.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] For example, there is a significant difference in access to both water and humidity between temperate rain forests and deserts.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] This difference in water availability causes a diversity in the organisms that survive in these areas.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] These differences in abiotic components alter the species present by creating boundaries of what species can survive within the environment and influencing competition between two species.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors such as salinity can give one species a competitive advantage over another, creating pressures that lead to speciation and alteration of a species to and from generalist and specialist competitors.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress is essentially unavoidable.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress affects animals, but plants are especially dependent, if not solely dependent, on environmental factors, so it is particularly constraining.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress is the most harmful factor concerning the growth and productivity of crops worldwide.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Research has also shown that abiotic stressors are at their most harmful when they occur together, in combinations of abiotic stress factors.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] The most common of the stressors are the easiest for people to identify, but there are many other, less recognizable abiotic stress factors which affect environments constantly.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Lesser-known stressors generally occur on a smaller scale.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] They include: poor edaphic conditions like rock content and pH levels, high radiation, compaction, contamination, and other, highly specific conditions like rapid rehydration during seed germination.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress, as a natural part of every ecosystem, will affect organisms in a variety of ways.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Although these effects may be either beneficial or detrimental, the location of the area is crucial in determining the extent of the impact that abiotic stress will have.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] The higher the latitude of the area affected, the greater the impact of abiotic stress will be on that area.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] So, a taiga or boreal forest is at the mercy of whatever abiotic stress factors may come along, while tropical zones are much less susceptible to such stressors.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] While abiotic stress may have negative impacts on individual organisms, there are cases where abiotic stress plays an important role in maintaining a healthy ecosystem.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Important ecosystem mechanisms and improved overall stress tolerance may rely on occasional low levels of abiotic stress.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] One example of a situation where abiotic stress plays a constructive role in an ecosystem is in natural wildfires.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Smaller fires are useful in reducing the overall fuel load of an area of forest or prairie.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] By clearing out dead brush and other organic matter, the risk of catastrophic and widespread fire decreases, and the residual ash of smaller fires helps add nutrients back into the soil.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] The observed benefits of these smaller and more controlled fires on land usability and species populations have led to the use of prescribed burning by humans for centuries.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Varying perspectives on the benefits and risks of fire to ecosystems have influenced official policy through history.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Forest Service, initially focused on fire control, changed its policy to one of fire management in 1974, recognizing these fires as a natural part of an ecosystem.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] There is also evidence that a diverse fire history between patches of land within an area has been shown to benefit transitional landscapes between savanna and forest.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Even though it is healthy for an ecosystem, a wildfire can still be considered an abiotic stressor, because it puts stress on individual organisms within the area.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] On the larger scale, though, natural wildfires are positive manifestations of abiotic stress.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] What also needs to be taken into account when looking for benefits of abiotic stress, is that one phenomenon may not affect an entire ecosystem in the same way.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] While a flood will kill most plants living low on the ground in a certain area, if there is rice there, it will thrive in the wet conditions.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Another example of this is in phytoplankton and zooplankton.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] The same types of conditions are usually considered stressful for these two types of organisms.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] They act very similarly when exposed to ultraviolet light and most toxins, but at elevated temperatures the phytoplankton reacts negatively, while the thermophilic zooplankton reacts positively to the increase in temperature.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] The two may be living in the same environment, but an increase in temperature of the area would prove stressful only for one of the organisms.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Lastly, abiotic stress has enabled species to grow, develop, and evolve, through the process of natural selection.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Heritable traits that improve an organism's resiliency under stressed conditions increase the likelihood that the organism will survive and reproduce, enabling it to pass these traits to the next generation.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Both plants and animals have evolved mechanisms allowing them to survive extremes.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] One of the detriments concerning abiotic stress involves farming.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] It has been claimed by one study that abiotic stress causes the most crop loss of any other factor and that most major crops are reduced in their yield by more than 50% from their potential yield.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Because abiotic stress is widely considered a detrimental effect, the research on this branch of the issue is extensive.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] For more information on the harmful effects of abiotic stress, see the sections below on plants and animals.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] A plant's first line of defense against abiotic stress is in its roots.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] If the soil holding the plant is healthy and biologically diverse, the plant will have a higher chance of surviving stressful conditions.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] The plant responses to stress are dependent on the tissue or organ affected by the stress.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] For example, transcriptional responses to stress are tissue or cell specific in roots and are quite different depending on the stress involved.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] One of the primary responses to abiotic stress such as high salinity is the disruption of the Na+/K+ ratio in the cytoplasm of the plant cell.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] High concentrations of Na+, for example, can decrease the capacity for the plant to take up water and also alter enzyme and transporter functions.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Evolved adaptations to efficiently restore cellular ion homeostasis have led to a wide variety of stress tolerant plants.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Facilitation, or the positive interactions between different species of plants, is an intricate web of association in a natural environment.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] In areas of high stress, the level of facilitation is especially high as well.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] This could possibly be because the plants need a stronger network to survive in a harsher environment, so their interactions between species, such as cross-pollination or mutualistic actions, become more common to cope with the severity of their habitat.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Plants also adapt very differently from one another, even from a plant living in the same area.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] When a group of different plant species was prompted by a variety of different stress signals, such as drought or cold, each plant responded uniquely.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Hardly any of the responses were similar, even though the plants had become accustomed to exactly the same home environment.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Serpentine soils (media with low concentrations of nutrients and high concentrations of heavy metals) can be a source of abiotic stress.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Initially, the absorption of toxic metal ions is limited by cell membrane exclusion.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Ions that are absorbed into tissues are sequestered in cell vacuoles.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] This sequestration mechanism is facilitated by proteins on the vacuole membrane.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] An example of plants that adapt to serpentine soil are Metallophytes, or hyperaccumulators, as they are known for their ability to absorbed heavy metals using the root-to-shoot translocation (which it will absorb into shoots rather than the plant itself).
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] They're also extinguished for their ability to absorb toxic substances from heavy metals.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Chemical priming has been proposed to increase tolerance to abiotic stresses in crop plants.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] In this method, which is analogous to vaccination, stress-inducing chemical agents are introduced to the plant in brief doses so that the plant begins preparing defense mechanisms.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Thus, when the abiotic stress occurs, the plant has already prepared defense mechanisms that can be activated faster and increase tolerance.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress mostly affects plants used in agriculture.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Some examples of adverse conditions (which may be caused by climate change) are high or low temperatures, drought, salinity, and toxins.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Elevated global temperatures present a severe bottleneck for crop yields, as heat stress alters membrane fluidity, accelerates destructive transpiration rates, and heavily impairs a plant's overall Water Use Efficiency (WUE).
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] When crops encounter extreme thermal environments during early reproductive or vegetative stages, cellular homeostasis is broken down, causing grain yield reduction and premature leaf senescence.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] To mitigate down-stream damage from overlapping thermal and drought shocks, advanced ex-ante strategies such as physical seed priming or chemical priming agents are applied.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] These priming interventions activate early molecular, enzymatic, and hormonal pre-defense responses within the seed tissue, enabling the plant to maintain higher functional stability and lower oxidative injury when heat stress occurs later in the field environment.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Flooding acts as a compound environmental stressor that is broadly categorized into waterlogging (where only the root system is inundated) and complete submergence (where the entire plant is covered by water).
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] The primary hazard of flooding is gas diffusion restriction, which triggers oxygen starvation (hypoxia or anoxia) in the rhizosphere and alters essential plant hormone signaling networks, such as the regulation between Sub1A and non-Sub1A genotypes in rice.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] To cope with complete submergence, tolerant plants rely on distinct physiological survival strategies.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Furthermore, monitoring maximum quantum yield performance reveals that preserving photosynthetic efficiency during transient flooding stress is paramount to driving rapid physiological recovery once the water recedes.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Soil acidity acts as a sweeping abiotic stress factor on global arable lands, primarily because low pH environments trigger dangerous chemical toxicities dominated by soluble aluminum (Al3+ )and iron, which structurally damage root anatomy and limit basic development.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] High acidity also locks up vital macronutrients, causing severe phosphorus starvation stress that forces plants to aggressively modify their lateral root structures to maximize surface area absorption.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] To remediate heavy-metal-polluted and highly acidic substrates, bioremediation utilizes hyperaccumulator plant traits (metallophytes).
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] These specialized plants successfully survive the toxicity of acidic media by relying on a highly developed root-to-shoot translocation system, which efficiently absorbs and transports toxic ions away from fragile root tissues and sequesters them safely inside the upper shoot vacuoles.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Soil salinization, the accumulation of water-soluble salts to levels that negatively impact plant production, is a global phenomenon affecting approximately 831 million hectares of land.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] More specifically, the phenomenon threatens 19.5% of the world's irrigated agricultural land and 2.1% of the world's non-irrigated (dry-land) agricultural lands.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] High soil salinity content can be harmful to plants because water-soluble salts can alter osmotic potential gradients and consequently inhibit many cellular functions.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Over generations, many plants have mutated and built different mechanisms to counter salinity effects.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] A good combatant of salinity in plants is the hormone ethylene.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Ethylene is known for regulating plant growth and development and dealing with stress conditions.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Many central membrane proteins in plants, such as ETO2, ERS1 and EIN2, are used for ethylene signaling in many plant growth processes.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Mutations in these proteins can lead to heightened salt sensitivity and can limit plant growth.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] The effects of salinity has been studied on *Arabidopsis* plants that have mutated ERS1, ERS2, ETR1, ETR2 and EIN4 proteins.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] These proteins are used for ethylene signaling against certain stress conditions, such as salt and the ethylene precursor ACC is used to suppress any sensitivity to the salt stress.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Phosphorus (P) is an essential macronutrient required for plant growth and development, but it is present only in limited quantities in most of the world's soil.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Plants use P mainly in the form of soluble inorganic phosphates (PO4−−−) but are subject to abiotic stress when there is not enough soluble PO4−−− in the soil.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Phosphorus forms insoluble complexes with Ca and Mg in alkaline soils and with Al and Fe in acidic soils that make the phosphorus unavailable for plant roots.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] It has been shown that PHR1, a MYB-related transcription factor, is a master regulator of P-starvation response in plants.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Drought stress, defined as naturally occurring water deficit, is a main cause of crop losses in agriculture.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] This is because water is essential for many fundamental processes in plant growth.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] It has become especially important in recent years to find a way to combat drought stress.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] A decrease in precipitation and consequent increase in drought are extremely likely in the future due to an increase in global warming.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Plants have come up with many mechanisms and adaptations to try and deal with drought stress.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] One of the leading ways that plants combat drought stress is by closing their stomata.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] A key hormone regulating stomatal opening and closing is abscisic acid (ABA).
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Synthesis of ABA causes the ABA to bind to receptors.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] This binding then affects the opening of ion channels, thereby decreasing turgor pressure in the stomata and causing them to close.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Recent studies by Gonzalez-Villagra, et al., have shown how ABA levels increased in drought-stressed plants (2018).
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] They showed that when plants were placed in a stressful situation, they produced more ABA to try to conserve any water they had in their leaves.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Another extremely important factor in dealing with drought stress and regulating the uptake and export of water is aquaporins (AQPs).
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] AQPs are integral membrane proteins that make up channels.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] These channels' main job is the transport of water and other essential solutes.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] AQPs are both transcriptionally and post-transcriptionally regulated by many different factors such as ABA, GA3, pH and Ca2+; and the specific levels of AQPs in certain parts of the plant, such as roots or leaves, helps to draw as much water into the plant as possible.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] By understanding the mechanisms of both AQPs and the hormone ABA, scientists will be better able to produce drought-resistant plants in the future.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] A study by Tombesi et al., found that plants which had previously been exposed to drought were able to minimize water loss and decrease water use.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] They found that plants which were exposed to drought conditions actually changed the way they regulated their stomata and what they called "hydraulic safety margin" so as to decrease the vulnerability of the plant.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] By changing the regulation of stomata and subsequently the transpiration, plants were able to function better when less water was available.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] For animals, the most stressful of all the abiotic stressors is heat.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] This is because many species are unable to regulate their internal body temperature.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Even in the species that are able to regulate their own temperature, it is not always a completely accurate system.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Temperature determines metabolic rates, heart rates, and other very important factors within the bodies of animals, so an extreme temperature change can easily distress the animal's body.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Animals can respond to extreme heat, for example, through natural heat acclimation or by burrowing into the ground to find a cooler space.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] It is also possible to see in animals that a high genetic diversity is beneficial in providing resiliency against harsh abiotic stressors.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] This acts as a sort of stock room when a species is plagued by the perils of natural selection.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] A variety of galling insects are among the most specialized and diverse herbivores on the planet, and their extensive protections against abiotic stress factors have helped the insect in gaining that position of honor.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Biodiversity is determined by many things, and one of them is abiotic stress.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] If an environment is highly stressful, biodiversity tends to be low.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] If abiotic stress does not have a strong presence in an area, the biodiversity will be much higher.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] This idea leads into the understanding of how abiotic stress and endangered species are related.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] It has been observed through a variety of environments that as the level of abiotic stress increases, the number of species decreases.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] This means that species are more likely to become population threatened, endangered, and even extinct, when and where abiotic stress is especially harsh.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Data suggests that anthropogenic activity has increased the global temperature, and likely increased the odds of extreme climate events such as drought, fire conditions and flooding.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] Threats to organisms and ecosystem biodiversity due to increased abiotic stress are one major impact of this change.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] The effects of climate change on biomes vary due to the location, patterns of precipitation, and the organisms which inhabit them.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] On the species level, the increased abiotic stress due to climate change can lead to adaptations which increase a species' reproductive success under these conditions.
[src:bacteriophage/abiotic-stress] However, such highly specialized adaptations may leave species vulnerable to other stresses.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] In ecology, **local abundance** is the relative representation of a species in a particular ecosystem.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] It is usually measured as the number of individuals found per sample.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] The ratio of abundance of one species to one or multiple other species living in an ecosystem is referred to as relative species abundances.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] Both indicators are relevant for computing biodiversity.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] A variety of sampling methods are used to measure abundance.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] For larger animals, these may include spotlight counts, track counts and roadkill counts, as well as presence at monitoring stations.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] In many plant communities the abundances of plant species are measured by plant cover, i.e. the relative area covered by different plant species in a small plot.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] Abundance is in simplest terms usually measured by identifying and counting every individual of every species in a given sector.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] It is common for the distribution of species to be skewed so that a few species take up the bulk of individuals collected.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] Relative species abundance is calculated by dividing the number of species from one group by the total number of species from all groups.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] These measures are all a part of community ecology.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] Understanding patterns within a community is easy when the community has a relatively low number of species.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] However most communities do not have a low number of species.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] Measuring species abundance allows for understanding of how species are distributed within an ecosystem.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] For example, salt water marshes have an influx of sea water, causing only a few species which are adapted to be able to survive in both salt and fresh water to be abundant.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] Inversely in land locked wetlands, the species abundance is more evenly distributed among the species who live within the wetland.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] In most ecosystems in which abundance has been calculated, most often only a small number of species are abundant, while a large number are pretty rare.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] These abundant species are often generalists, with many rare species being specialists.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] High density of a species in multiple localities will usually lead to it being relatively abundant over all in an ecosystem.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] Therefore, high local abundance can be directly linked to high regional distribution.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] Species with high abundance are likely to have more offspring, and these offspring in turn are more likely to colonize a new sector of the ecosystem than a species which is less abundant.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] Thus begins a positive feedback loop leading to a species distribution in which a few "core species" are wide spread, and the other species are restricted and scarce known as satellite species.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] Species abundance distribution (SAD) is one of the main uses of this measurement.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] SAD is a measurement of how common, or rare species are within an ecosystem.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] This allows researchers to assess how different species are distributed throughout an ecosystem.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] SAD is one of the most basic measurements in ecology and is used very often, therefore many different methods of measurement and analysis have developed.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] There are several methods for measuring abundance.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] An example of this is Semi-Quantitive Abundance ratings.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] These are measurement methods which involve estimation based on viewing a specific area of a designated size.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] The two Semi-Quantitive Abundance ratings used are known as the D.A.F.O.R, and the A.C.F.O.R.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] These methods are useful for getting a rough estimate of the species abundance in a designated area (quadrant), but they are not exact or objective measurements.
[src:bacteriophage/abundance-ecology] Therefore, if another method of measuring abundance is available, it should be used, as this will lead to more useful and quantifiable data.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] When consumed in a metabolic process, ATP converts either to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) or to adenosine monophosphate (AMP).
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Other processes, such as oxidative phosphorylation or substrate-level phosphorylation, regenerate ATP.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a precursor to DNA and RNA, and is used as a coenzyme.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Daily, an average adult human recycles through synthesis and hydrolysis around 50 kilograms of ATP (about 100 moles).
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] From the perspective of biochemistry, ATP is classified as a nucleoside triphosphate, which indicates that it consists of three components: a nitrogenous base (adenine), the sugar ribose, and the triphosphate.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP consists of three parts: a sugar, an amine base, and a phosphate group.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] More specifically, ATP consists of an adenine attached by the #9-nitrogen atom to the 1′ carbon atom of a sugar (ribose), which in turn is attached at the 5' carbon atom of the sugar to a triphosphate group.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] In its many reactions related to metabolism, the adenine and sugar groups remain unchanged, but the triphosphate is converted to di- and monophosphate, giving respectively the derivatives ADP and AMP.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The three phosphoryl groups are labeled as alpha (α), beta (β), and, for the terminal phosphate, gamma (γ).
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] In neutral solution, ionized ATP exists mostly as ATP4−, with a small proportion of ATP3−.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Polyanionic and featuring a potentially chelating polyphosphate group, ATP binds metal cations with high affinity.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding constant for Mg2+ is (9554).
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding of a divalent cation, almost always magnesium, strongly affects the interaction of ATP with various proteins.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Due to the strength of the ATP-Mg2+ interaction, ATP exists in the cell mostly as a complex with Mg2+ bonded to the phosphate oxygen centers.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] A second magnesium ion is critical for ATP binding in the kinase domain.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The presence of Mg2+ regulates kinase activity.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] It is interesting from an RNA world perspective that ATP can carry a Mg2+ ion which catalyzes RNA polymerization.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Salts of ATP can be isolated as colorless solids.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is stable in aqueous solutions between pH 6.8 and 7.4 (in the absence of catalysts).
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] At more extreme pH levels, it rapidly hydrolyses to ADP and phosphate.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Living cells maintain the ratio of ATP to ADP at a point ten orders of magnitude from equilibrium, with ATP concentrations fivefold higher than the concentration of ADP.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] In the context of biochemical reactions, the P-O-P bonds are frequently referred to as *high-energy bonds*.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] releases Δ*G*°' = −30.5 kJ/mol (−7.3 kcal/mol) of Gibbs free energy under standard conditions when all metabolite concentrations are 1 mol/L.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] This may differ under physiological conditions if the reactant and products are not exactly in these ionization states.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] At cytoplasmic conditions, where the ADP/ATP ratio is 10 orders of magnitude from equilibrium, the Δ*G* is around −57 kJ/mol.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Along with pH, the free energy change of ATP hydrolysis is also associated with Mg2+ concentration, from ΔG°' = −35.7 kJ/mol at a Mg2+ concentration of zero, to ΔG°' = −31 kJ/mol at [Mg2+] = 5 mM.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Higher concentrations of Mg2+ decrease free energy released in the reaction due to binding of Mg2+ ions to negatively charged oxygen atoms of ATP at pH 7.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] A typical intracellular concentration of ATP is 1–10 μmol per gram of muscle tissue in a variety of eukaryotes.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The dephosphorylation of ATP and rephosphorylation of ADP and AMP occur repeatedly in the course of aerobic metabolism.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can be produced by a number of distinct cellular processes; the three main pathways in eukaryotes are (1) glycolysis, (2) the citric acid cycle/oxidative phosphorylation, and (3) beta-oxidation.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The overall process of oxidizing glucose to carbon dioxide, the combination of pathways 1 and 2, known as cellular respiration, produces about 30 equivalents of ATP from each molecule of glucose.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP production by a non-photosynthetic aerobic eukaryote occurs mainly in the mitochondria, which comprise nearly 25% of the volume of a typical cell.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] In glycolysis, glucose and glycerol are metabolized to pyruvate.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis generates two equivalents of ATP through substrate phosphorylation catalyzed by two enzymes, phosphoglycerate kinase (PGK) and pyruvate kinase.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Two equivalents of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) are also produced, which can be oxidized via the electron transport chain and result in the generation of additional ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The pyruvate generated as an end-product of glycolysis is a substrate for the citric acid cycle.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is viewed as consisting of two phases with five steps each.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] In phase 1, "the preparatory phase", glucose is converted to 2 d-glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate (g3p).
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] One ATP is invested in Step 1, and another ATP is invested in Step 3.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Steps 1 and 3 of glycolysis are referred to as "Priming Steps".
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] In Phase 2, two equivalents of g3p are converted to two pyruvates.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Also, in Step 10, two further equivalents of ATP are produced.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] In Steps 7 and 10, ATP is generated from ADP.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] A net of two ATPs is formed in the glycolysis cycle.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The glycolysis pathway is later associated with the Citric Acid Cycle, which produces additional equivalents of ATP.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is regulated allosterically by a number of metabolic compounds.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] For example, hexokinase is directly inhibited by its product, glucose-6-phosphate, and pyruvate kinase is inhibited by ATP itself.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The main control point for the glycolytic pathway is phosphofructokinase 1 (PFK1), which is allosterically inhibited by high concentrations of ATP and activated by high concentrations of AMP.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The inhibition of PFK1 by ATP is unusual since ATP is also a substrate in the reaction catalyzed by PFK1.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The active form of PFK1 enzyme is a tetramer that exists in two conformations, only one of which binds the second substrate fructose-6-phosphate (F6P).
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The PFK1 enzyme has two binding sites for ATP – the active site is accessible in either protein conformation, but ATP binding to the inhibitor site stabilizes the conformation that binds F6P poorly.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] A number of other small molecules can compensate for the ATP-induced shift in equilibrium conformation and reactivate PFK1, including cyclic AMP, ammonium ions, inorganic phosphate, fructose 1,6-bisphosphate and fructose 2,6-bisphosphate.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] In the mitochondrion, pyruvate is oxidized by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex to the acetyl group, which is fully oxidized to carbon dioxide by the citric acid cycle.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] NADH and FADH2 are recycled (to NAD+ and FAD, respectively) by oxidative phosphorylation, generating additional ATP.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The oxidation of NADH results in the synthesis of 2–3 equivalents of ATP, and the oxidation of one FADH2 yields between 1–2 equivalents of ATP.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of cellular ATP is generated by this process.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Although the citric acid cycle itself does not involve molecular oxygen, it is an obligately aerobic process because O2 is used to recycle the NADH and FADH2.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] In the absence of oxygen, the citric acid cycle ceases.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The generation of ATP by the mitochondrion from cytosolic NADH relies on the malate-aspartate shuttle (and to a lesser extent, the glycerol-phosphate shuttle) because the inner mitochondrial membrane is impermeable to NADH and NAD+.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Instead of transferring the generated NADH, a malate dehydrogenase enzyme converts oxaloacetate to malate, which is translocated to the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Another malate dehydrogenase-catalyzed reaction occurs in the opposite direction, producing oxaloacetate and NADH from the newly transported malate and the mitochondrion's interior store of NAD+.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] A transaminase converts the oxaloacetate to aspartate for transport back across the membrane and into the intermembrane space.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the passage of electrons from NADH and FADH2 through the electron transport chain releases the energy to pump protons out of the mitochondrial matrix and into the intermembrane space.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] This pumping generates a proton motive force that is the net effect of a pH gradient and an electric potential gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Flow of protons down this potential gradient – that is, from the intermembrane space to the matrix – yields ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Most of the ATP synthesized in the mitochondria will be used for cellular processes in the cytosol; thus it must be exported from its site of synthesis in the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP outward movement is favored by the inner mitochondrial membrane's electrochemical potential because the cytosol has a relatively positive charge compared to the relatively negative matrix.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] For every ATP transported out, it costs 1 H+.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Therefore, making and exporting one ATP requires 4H+.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The inner membrane contains an antiporter, the ADP/ATP translocase, which is an integral membrane protein used to exchange newly synthesized ATP in the matrix for ADP in the intermembrane space.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The citric acid cycle is regulated mainly by the availability of key substrates, particularly the ratio of NAD+ to NADH and the concentrations of calcium, inorganic phosphate, ATP, ADP, and AMP.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Citrate – the ion that gives its name to the cycle – is a feedback inhibitor of citrate synthase and also inhibits PFK, providing a direct link between the regulation of the citric acid cycle and glycolysis.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] In the presence of air and various cofactors and enzymes, fatty acids are converted to acetyl-CoA.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Each cycle of beta-oxidation shortens the fatty acid chain by two carbon atoms and produces one equivalent each of acetyl-CoA, NADH, and FADH2.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The acetyl-CoA is metabolized by the citric acid cycle to generate ATP, while the NADH and FADH2 are used by oxidative phosphorylation to generate ATP.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Dozens of ATP equivalents are generated by the beta-oxidation of a single long acyl chain.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the key control point is the reaction catalyzed by cytochrome c oxidase, which is regulated by the availability of its substrate – the reduced form of cytochrome c.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, a high ratio of [NADH] to [NAD+] or a high ratio of [ADP] [Pi] to [ATP] imply a high amount of reduced cytochrome c and a high level of cytochrome c oxidase activity.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] An additional level of regulation is introduced by the transport rates of ATP and NADH between the mitochondrial matrix and the cytoplasm.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies can be used as fuels, yielding 22 ATP and 2 GTP molecules per acetoacetate molecule when oxidized in the mitochondria.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies are transported from the liver to other tissues, where acetoacetate and *beta*-hydroxybutyrate can be reconverted to acetyl-CoA to produce reducing equivalents (NADH and FADH2), via the citric acid cycle.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies cannot be used as fuel by the liver, because the liver lacks the enzyme β-ketoacyl-CoA transferase, also called thiolase.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in low concentrations is taken up by the liver and undergoes detoxification through the methylglyoxal pathway which ends with lactate.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in high concentrations is absorbed by cells other than those in the liver and enters a different pathway via 1,2-propanediol.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Though the pathway follows a different series of steps requiring ATP, 1,2-propanediol can be turned into pyruvate.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Fermentation is the metabolism of organic compounds in the absence of air.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] It involves substrate-level phosphorylation in the absence of a respiratory electron transport chain.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Anaerobic respiration is respiration in the absence of O2.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Prokaryotes can utilize a variety of electron acceptors.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] These include nitrate, sulfate, and carbon dioxide.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] In anaerobic organisms and prokaryotes, different pathways result in ATP.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is produced in the chloroplasts of green plants in a process similar to oxidative phosphorylation, called photophosphorylation.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can also be synthesized through several so-called "replenishment" reactions catalyzed by the enzyme families of nucleoside diphosphate kinases (NDKs), which use other nucleoside triphosphates as a high-energy phosphate donor, and the ATP:guanido-phosphotransferase family.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] In plants, ATP is synthesized in the thylakoid membrane of the chloroplast.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is called photophosphorylation.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The "machinery" is similar to that in mitochondria except that light energy is used to pump protons across a membrane to produce a proton-motive force.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP synthase then ensues exactly as in oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Some of the ATP produced in the chloroplasts is consumed in the Calvin cycle, which produces triose sugars.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The total quantity of ATP in the human body is about 0.1 mol/L.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of ATP is recycled from ADP by the aforementioned processes.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, at any given time, the total amount of ATP + ADP remains fairly constant.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The energy used by human cells in an adult requires the hydrolysis of 100 to 150 mol/L of ATP daily, which means a human will typically use their body weight worth of ATP over the course of the day.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Each equivalent of ATP is recycled 1000–1500 times during a single day (150 / 0.1 = 1500), at approximately 9×1020 molecules/s.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The conversion of ATP to ADP is the principal mechanism for energy supply in biological processes.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] However, removing a phosphate group from ADP to produce adenosine monophosphate (AMP) also produces extra energy.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is involved in signal transduction by serving as substrate for kinases, enzymes that transfer phosphate groups.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Kinases are the most common ATP-binding proteins.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] They share a small number of common folds.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Phosphorylation of a protein by a kinase can activate a cascade such as the mitogen-activated protein kinase cascade.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a substrate of adenylate cyclase, most commonly in G protein-coupled receptor signal transduction pathways and is transformed to second messenger, cyclic AMP, which is involved in triggering calcium signals by the release of calcium from intracellular stores.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] This form of signal transduction is particularly important in brain function, although it is involved in the regulation of a multitude of other cellular processes.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is one of four monomers required in the synthesis of RNA.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is promoted by RNA polymerases.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] A similar process occurs in the formation of DNA, except that ATP is first converted to the deoxyribonucleotide dATP.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Like many condensation reactions in nature, DNA replication and DNA transcription also consume ATP.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase enzymes consume ATP in the attachment tRNA to amino acids, forming aminoacyl-tRNA complexes.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl transferase binds AMP-amino acid to tRNA.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The amino acid is coupled to the penultimate nucleotide at the 3′-end of the tRNA (the A in the sequence CCA) via an ester bond (roll over in illustration).
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Transporting chemicals out of a cell against a gradient is often associated with ATP hydrolysis.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Transport is mediated by ATP binding cassette transporters.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The human genome encodes 48 ABC transporters, that are used for exporting drugs, lipids, and other compounds.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells secrete ATP to communicate with other cells in a process called purinergic signalling.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP serves as a neurotransmitter in many parts of the nervous system, modulates ciliary beating, affects vascular oxygen supply etc.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is either secreted directly across the cell membrane through channel proteins or is pumped into vesicles which then fuse with the membrane.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells detect ATP using the purinergic receptor proteins P2X and P2Y.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has been shown to be a critically important signalling molecule for microglia - neuron interactions in the adult brain, as well as during brain development.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Furthermore, tissue-injury induced ATP-signalling is a major factor in rapid microglial phenotype changes.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Muscle contractions are regulated by signaling pathways, although different muscle types being regulated by specific pathways and stimuli based on their particular function.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] However, in all muscle types, contraction is performed by the proteins actin and myosin.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] When ATPase hydrolyzes the bound ATP into ADP and inorganic phosphate, myosin is positioned in a way that it can bind to actin.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Myosin bound by ADP and Pi forms cross-bridges with actin and the subsequent release of ADP and Pi releases energy as the power stroke.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The power stroke causes actin filament to slide past the myosin filament, shortening the muscle and causing a contraction.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Another ATP molecule can then bind to myosin, releasing it from actin and allowing this process to repeat.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has recently been proposed to act as a biological hydrotrope and has been shown to affect proteome-wide solubility.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetyl phosphate (AcP), a precursor to ATP, can readily be synthesized at modest yields from thioacetate in pH 7 and 20 °C and pH 8 and 50 °C, although acetyl phosphate is less stable in warmer temperatures and alkaline conditions than in cooler and acidic to neutral conditions.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] It is unable to promote polymerization of ribonucleotides and amino acids and was only capable of phosphorylation of organic compounds.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that it can promote aggregation and stabilization of AMP in the presence of Na+, aggregation of nucleotides could promote polymerization above 75 °C in the absence of Na+.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] It is possible that polymerization promoted by AcP could occur at mineral surfaces.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that ADP can only be phosphorylated to ATP by AcP and other nucleoside triphosphates were not phosphorylated by AcP.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] This might explain why all lifeforms use ATP to drive biochemical reactions.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Biochemistry laboratories often use *in vitro* studies to explore ATP-dependent molecular processes.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP analogs are also used in X-ray crystallography to determine a protein structure in complex with ATP, often together with other substrates.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Enzyme inhibitors of ATP-dependent enzymes such as kinases are needed to examine the binding sites and transition states involved in ATP-dependent reactions.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Most useful ATP analogs cannot be hydrolyzed as ATP would be; instead, they trap the enzyme in a structure closely related to the ATP-bound state.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Adenosine 5′-(γ-thiotriphosphate) is an extremely common ATP analog in which one of the gamma-phosphate oxygens is replaced by a sulfur atom; this anion is hydrolyzed at a dramatically slower rate than ATP itself and functions as an inhibitor of ATP-dependent processes.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] In crystallographic studies, hydrolysis transition states are modeled by the bound vanadate ion.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Caution is warranted in interpreting the results of experiments using ATP analogs, since some enzymes can hydrolyze them at appreciable rates at high concentration.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is used intravenously for some heart-related conditions.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP was discovered in 1929 from muscle tissue by Karl Lohmann and Jendrassik and, independently, by Cyrus Fiske and Yellapragada Subba Rao of Harvard Medical School, both teams competing against each other to find an assay for phosphorus.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] It was proposed to be the intermediary between energy-yielding and energy-requiring reactions in cells by Fritz Albert Lipmann in 1941.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] He played a major role in establishing that ATP is the energy currency of a cell.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] It was first synthesized in the laboratory by Alexander Todd in 1948, and he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1957 partly for this work.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1978 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Peter Dennis Mitchell for the discovery of the chemiosmotic mechanism of ATP synthesis.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was divided, one half jointly to Paul D.
[src:bacteriophage/adenosine-triphosphate] Walker "for their elucidation of the enzymatic mechanism underlying the synthesis of adenosine triphosphate (ATP)" and the other half to Jens C.
[src:bacteriophage/ainoaviricetes] The genome is circular single-stranded DNA of about 9200 nucleotides in length.
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] Hershey was born in Owosso, Michigan to Robert Day and Alma Wilbur Hershey.
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] He earned a B.S. in chemistry in 1930, and Ph.D. in bacteriology in 1934 from Michigan State University.
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] Shortly after, Hershey accepted a faculty position at Washington University in St.
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] Louis, serving as an instructor of bacteriology and immunology from 1934 to 1950.
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] At Washington University, Hershey worked closely with department head Jacques Bronfenbrenner to investigate bacteriophages, or phages**—**viruses that infect and replicate inside bacteria.
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] Hershey's work on the factors impacting the virus' ability to infect its targets brought him to the attention of fellow phage researchers Max Delbrück and Salvador Luria.
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] In 1943, Delbrück invited Hershey to Vanderbilt University to discuss his phage research.
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] Together, with Luria, they would form the core of an informal network of researchers called "the Phage group".
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] Three years later, Hershey and Delbrück would independently discover that different strains of bacteriophage can both exchange genetic material when infecting the same bacterial cell.
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] This process results in hybrid phages containing genetic material from both sources, which Hershey referred to as "genetic recombination".
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] Hershey left Washington University in 1950 for the Department of Genetics of the Carnegie Institution of Washington, a predecessor of Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory.
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] Two years later, he and Martha Chase would conduct the famous Hershey–Chase, or "Waring Blender" experiment.
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] Their work confirmed that DNA, not protein, was the genetic material of life.
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] In 1962, Hershey was named director of the Department of Genetics, a position he held until his retirement in 1970.
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] He would live on the grounds of Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory for the rest of his life.
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] Although officially retired from scientific research, Hershey would continue to pursue new projects.
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] In 1971, he edited *The Bacteriophage λ*, an extensive volume on the subject, published by CSHL Press that same year.
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] In 1981, Hershey became a founding member of the World Cultural Council.
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] Hershey died from congestive heart failure on May 22, 1997 at his home in Laurel Hollow, New York.
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] At the time, he was survived by his wife Harriet Davidson (1918–2000) and their only child, Peter Manning Hershey (1956–1999).
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] Following his death, Frank Stahl, a member of The Phage Group, wrote: "The Phage Church, as we were sometimes called (see Phage group), was led by the Trinity of Delbrück, Luria, and Hershey.
[src:bacteriophage/alfred-hershey] Delbrück's status as founder and his *ex cathedra* manner made him the pope, of course, and Luria was the hard-working, socially sensitive priest-confessor.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] A **bacteriophage** (/bækˈtɪrioʊfeɪdʒ/), also known informally as a **phage** (/ˈfeɪdʒ/), is a virus that infects and replicates within bacteria.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The term is derived from Ancient Greek φαγεῖν*(phagein)* 'to devour' and *bacteria*.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are composed of proteins that encapsulate a DNA or RNA genome, and may have structures that are either simple or elaborate.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Their genomes may encode as few as four genes (e.g.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Phages replicate within the bacterium following the injection of their genome into its cytoplasm.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are among the most common and diverse entities in the biosphere.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are ubiquitous viruses, found wherever bacteria exist.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] It is estimated there are more than 1031 bacteriophages on the planet, more than every living organism on Earth, including bacteria, combined.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages were used from the 1920s as an alternative to antibiotics in the Soviet Union and Central Europe, as well as in France and Brazil.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] They are seen as a possible therapy against multi-drug-resistant strains of many bacteria.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are known to interact with the immune system both indirectly via bacterial expression of phage-encoded proteins and directly by influencing innate immunity and bacterial clearance.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Phage–host interactions are becoming increasingly important areas of research.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] In 1896, Ernest Hanbury Hankin reported that something in the waters of the Ganges and Yamuna rivers in India had a marked antibacterial action against cholera and it could pass through a very fine porcelain Chamberland filter.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] In 1915, British bacteriologist Frederick Twort, superintendent of the Brown Institution of London, discovered a small agent that infected and killed bacteria.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Twort's research was interrupted by the onset of World War I, as well as a shortage of funding and the discoveries of antibiotics.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Independently, French-Canadian microbiologist Félix d'Hérelle, working at the Pasteur Institute in Paris, announced on 3 September 1917 that he had discovered "an invisible, antagonistic microbe of the dysentery bacillus".
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] He also recorded a dramatic account of a man suffering from dysentery who was restored to good health by the bacteriophages.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] It was d'Hérelle who conducted much research into bacteriophages and introduced the concept of phage therapy.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] In 1919, in Paris, France, d'Hérelle conducted the first clinical application of a bacteriophage, with the first reported use in the United States being in 1922.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] In 1969, Max Delbrück, Alfred Hershey, and Salvador Luria were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discoveries of the replication of viruses and their genetic structure.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Specifically the work of Hershey, as contributor to the Hershey–Chase experiment in 1952, provided convincing evidence that DNA, not protein, was the genetic material of life.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Delbrück and Luria carried out the Luria–Delbrück experiment which demonstrated statistically that mutations in bacteria occur randomly and thus follow Darwinian rather than Lamarckian principles.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] In 2018, George Smith and Gregory Winter were awarded Nobel Prize in Chemistry for the phage display of peptides and antibodies.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Phages were discovered to be antibacterial agents and were used in the former Soviet Republic of Georgia (pioneered there by Giorgi Eliava with help from the co-discoverer of bacteriophages, Félix d'Hérelle) during the 1920s and 1930s for treating bacterial infections.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] They had widespread use, including treatment of soldiers in the Red Army.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The use of phages has continued since the end of the Cold War in Russia, Georgia, and elsewhere in Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The first regulated, randomized, double-blind clinical trial was reported in the *Journal of Wound Care* in June 2009, which evaluated the safety and efficacy of a bacteriophage cocktail to treat infected venous ulcers of the leg in human patients.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The FDA approved the study as a Phase I clinical trial.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The study's results demonstrated the safety of therapeutic application of bacteriophages, but did not show efficacy.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The authors explained that the use of certain chemicals that are part of standard wound care (e.g. lactoferrin or silver) may have interfered with bacteriophage viability.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Shortly after that, another controlled clinical trial in Western Europe (treatment of ear infections caused by *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*) was reported in the journal *Clinical Otolaryngology* in August 2009.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The study concludes that bacteriophage preparations were safe and effective for treatment of chronic ear infections in humans.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Additionally, there have been numerous animal and other experimental clinical trials evaluating the efficacy of bacteriophages for various diseases, such as infected burns and wounds, and cystic fibrosis-associated lung infections, among others.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] On the other hand, phages of *Inoviridae* have been shown to complicate biofilms involved in pneumonia and cystic fibrosis and to shelter the bacteria from drugs meant to eradicate disease, thus promoting persistent infection.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Meanwhile, bacteriophage researchers have been developing engineered viruses to overcome antibiotic resistance, and engineering the phage genes responsible for coding enzymes that degrade the biofilm matrix, phage structural proteins, and the enzymes responsible for lysis of the bacterial cell wall.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] There have been results showing that T4 phages that are small in size and short-tailed can be helpful in detecting *E. coli* in the human body.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Therapeutic efficacy of a phage cocktail was evaluated in a mouse model with nasal infection of multi-drug-resistant (MDR) *A. baumannii*.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Mice treated with the phage cocktail showed a 2.3-fold higher survival rate compared to those untreated at seven days post-infection.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] In 2017, a 68-year-old diabetic patient with necrotizing pancreatitis complicated by a pseudocyst infected with MDR *A. baumannii* strains was being treated with a cocktail of Azithromycin, Rifampicin, and Colistin for 4 months without results and overall rapidly declining health.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Once on the combination of the IV and PC therapy the patient's downward clinical trajectory reversed, and within two days he had awoken from his coma and become responsive.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] As his immune system began to function he had to be temporarily removed from the cocktail because his fever was spiking to over 104 °F (40 °C), but after two days the phage cocktails were re-introduced at levels he was able to tolerate.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The original three-antibiotic cocktail was replaced by minocycline after the bacterial strain was found not to be resistant to this and he rapidly regained full lucidity, although he was not discharged from the hospital until roughly 145 days after phage therapy began.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Phages have increasingly been used to safen food products and to forestall spoilage bacteria.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Since 2006, the United States Food and Drug Administration (FDA) and United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) have approved several bacteriophage products.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] LMP-102 (Intralytix) was approved for treating ready-to-eat (RTE) poultry and meat products.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] In that same year, the FDA approved LISTEX (developed and produced by Micreos) using bacteriophages on cheese to kill *Listeria monocytogenes* bacteria, in order to give them generally recognized as safe (GRAS) status.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] In July 2007, the same bacteriophage were approved for use on all food products.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] In 2011 USDA confirmed that LISTEX is a clean label processing aid and is included in USDA.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Research in the field of food safety is continuing to see if lytic phages are a viable option to control other food-borne pathogens in various food products.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Switzerland authorized a phage for use in cheese production in 2016.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The European Union has not yet (2025) authorized any.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages, including those specific to *Escherichia coli*, have been employed as indicators of fecal contamination in water sources.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Due to their shared structural and biological characteristics, coliphages can serve as proxies for viral fecal contamination and the presence of pathogenic viruses such as rotavirus, norovirus, and HAV.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Research conducted on wastewater treatment systems has revealed significant disparities in the behavior of coliphages compared to fecal coliforms, demonstrating a distinct correlation with the recovery of pathogenic viruses at the treatment's conclusion.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Establishing a secure discharge threshold, studies have determined that discharges below 3000 PFU/100 mL are considered safe in terms of limiting the release of pathogenic viruses.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] In 2011, the FDA cleared the first bacteriophage-based product for in vitro diagnostic use.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The KeyPath MRSA/MSSA Blood Culture Test uses a cocktail of bacteriophage to detect *Staphylococcus aureus* in positive blood cultures and determine methicillin resistance or susceptibility.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The test returns results in about five hours, compared to two to three days for standard microbial identification and susceptibility test methods.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] It was the first accelerated antibiotic-susceptibility test approved by the FDA.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Government agencies in the West have for several years been looking to Georgia and the former Soviet Union for help with exploiting phages for counteracting bioweapons and toxins, such as anthrax and botulism.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Developments are continuing among research groups in the U.S.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Other uses include spray application in horticulture for protecting plants and vegetable produce from decay and the spread of bacterial disease.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Other applications for bacteriophages are as biocides for environmental surfaces, e.g., in hospitals, and as preventative treatments for catheters and medical devices before use in clinical settings.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The technology for phages to be applied to dry surfaces, e.g., uniforms, curtains, or even sutures for surgery now exists.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Clinical trials reported in *Clinical Otolaryngology* show success in veterinary treatment of pet dogs with otitis.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The sensing of phage-triggered ion cascades (SEPTIC) bacterium sensing and identification method uses the ion emission and its dynamics during phage infection and offers high specificity and speed for detection.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Phage display is a different use of phages involving a library of phages with a variable peptide linked to a surface protein.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Each phage genome encodes the variant of the protein displayed on its surface (hence the name), providing a link between the peptide variant and its encoding gene.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Variant phages from the library may be selected through their binding affinity to an immobilized molecule (e.g., botulism toxin) to neutralize it.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The bound, selected phages can be multiplied by reinfecting a susceptible bacterial strain, thus allowing them to retrieve the peptides encoded in them for further study.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Phage proteins often have antimicrobial activity and may serve as leads for peptidomimetics, i.e. drugs that mimic peptides.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Phage-ligand technology makes use of phage proteins for various applications, such as binding of bacteria and bacterial components (e.g. endotoxin) and lysis of bacteria.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are important model organisms for studying principles of evolution and ecology.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Phages can be used to combat bacterial infections such as blackleg.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] A line of phage-based products is licensed in the United States, and Georgia has long used agricultural phages.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Elsewhere, research and pilot testing are still underway.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] This is notably the case in Switzerland, where research is being conducted by the Fribourg School of Engineering and Architecture in collaboration with the Lausanne University Hospital (CHUV).
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages present in the environment can cause cheese to not ferment.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] In order to avoid this, mixed-strain starter cultures and culture rotation regimes can be used.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Genetic engineering of culture microbes – especially *Lactococcus lactis* and *Streptococcus thermophilus* – have been studied for genetic analysis and modification to improve phage resistance.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] This has especially focused on plasmid and recombinant chromosomal modifications.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Some research has focused on the potential of bacteriophages as antimicrobial against foodborne pathogens and biofilm formation within the dairy industry.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] As the spread of antibiotic resistance is a main concern within the dairy industry, phages can serve as a promising alternative.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The life cycle of bacteriophages tends to be either a lytic cycle or a lysogenic cycle.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] In addition, some phages display pseudolysogenic behaviors.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] With *lytic phages* such as the T4 phage, bacterial cells are broken open (lysed) and destroyed after immediate replication of the virion.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] As soon as the cell is destroyed, the phage progeny can find new hosts to infect.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Lytic phages are more suitable for phage therapy.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Some lytic phages undergo a phenomenon known as lysis inhibition, where completed phage progeny will not immediately lyse out of the cell if extracellular phage concentrations are high.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] This mechanism is not identical to that of the temperate phage going dormant and usually is temporary.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] In contrast, the *lysogenic cycle* does not result in immediate lysing of the host cell.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Those phages able to undergo lysogeny are known as temperate phages.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Their viral genome will integrate with host DNA and replicate along with it, relatively harmlessly, or may even become established as a plasmid.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The virus remains dormant until host conditions deteriorate, perhaps due to depletion of nutrients, then, the endogenous phages (known as prophages) become active.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] At this point they initiate the reproductive cycle, resulting in lysis of the host cell.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] As the lysogenic cycle allows the host cell to continue to survive and reproduce, the virus is replicated in all offspring of the cell.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Sometimes prophages may provide benefits to the host bacterium while they are dormant by adding new functions to the bacterial genome, in a phenomenon called lysogenic conversion.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Examples are the conversion of harmless strains of *Corynebacterium diphtheriae* or *Vibrio cholerae* by bacteriophages to highly virulent ones that cause diphtheria or cholera, respectively.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Strategies to combat certain bacterial infections by targeting these toxin-encoding prophages have been proposed.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Bacterial cells are protected by a cell wall of polysaccharides, which are important virulence factors protecting bacterial cells against both immune host defenses and antibiotics.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] To enter a host cell, bacteriophages bind to specific receptors on the surface of bacteria, including lipopolysaccharides, teichoic acids, proteins, or even flagella.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] This specificity means a bacteriophage can infect only certain bacteria bearing receptors to which they can bind, which in turn, determines the phage's host range.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Polysaccharide-degrading enzymes are virion-associated proteins that enzymatically degrade the capsular outer layer of their hosts at the initial step of a tightly programmed phage infection process.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Host growth conditions also influence the ability of the phage to attach and invade them.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] As phage virions do not move independently, they must rely on random encounters with the correct receptors when in solution, such as blood, lymphatic circulation, irrigation, soil water, etc.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Myovirus bacteriophages use a hypodermic syringe-like motion to inject their genetic material into the cell.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] After contacting the appropriate receptor, the tail fibers flex to bring the base plate closer to the surface of the cell.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Once attached completely, irreversible binding is initiated and the tail contracts, possibly with the help of ATP present in the tail, injecting genetic material through the bacterial membrane.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The injection is accomplished through a sort of bending motion in the shaft by going to the side, contracting closer to the cell and pushing back up.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Podoviruses lack an elongated tail sheath like that of a myovirus, so instead, they use their small, tooth-like tail fibers enzymatically to degrade a portion of the cell membrane before inserting their genetic material.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Within minutes, bacterial ribosomes start translating viral mRNA into protein.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] For RNA-based phages, RNA replicase is synthesized early in the process.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Proteins modify the bacterial RNA polymerase so it preferentially transcribes viral mRNA.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The host's normal synthesis of proteins and nucleic acids is disrupted, and it is forced to manufacture viral products instead.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] These products go on to become part of new virions within the cell, helper proteins that contribute to the assemblage of new virions, or proteins involved in cell lysis.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] In 1972, Walter Fiers (University of Ghent, Belgium) was the first to establish the complete nucleotide sequence of a gene and in 1976, of the viral genome of bacteriophage MS2.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Some dsDNA bacteriophages encode ribosomal proteins, which are thought to modulate protein translation during phage infection.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] In the case of the T4 phage, the construction of new virus particles involves the assistance of helper proteins that act catalytically during phage morphogenesis.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The base plates are assembled first, with the tails being built upon them afterward.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The head capsids, constructed separately, will spontaneously assemble with the tails.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] During assembly of the phage T4 virion, the morphogenetic proteins encoded by the phage genes interact with each other in a characteristic sequence.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Maintaining an appropriate balance in the amounts of each of these proteins produced during viral infection appears to be critical for normal phage T4 morphogenesis.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The DNA is packed efficiently within the heads.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The whole process takes about 15 minutes.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Early studies of bacteriophage T4 (1962–1964) provided an opportunity to gain understanding of virtually all of the genes that are essential for growth of the bacteriophage under laboratory conditions.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] These studies were made possible by the availability of two classes of conditional lethal mutants.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] One class of such mutants was referred to as amber mutants.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The other class of conditional lethal mutants was referred to as temperature-sensitive mutants.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Studies of these two classes of mutants led to considerable insight into the functions and interactions of the proteins employed in the machinery of DNA replication, repair and recombination, and on how viruses are assembled from protein and nucleic acid components (molecular morphogenesis).
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Phages may be released via cell lysis, by extrusion, or, in a few cases, by budding.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Lysis, by tailed phages, is achieved by an enzyme called endolysin, which attacks and breaks down the cell wall peptidoglycan.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] An altogether different phage type, the filamentous phage, makes the host cell continually secrete new virus particles.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Released virions are described as free, and, unless defective, are capable of infecting a new bacterium.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Budding is associated with certain *Mycoplasma* phages.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] In contrast to virion release, phages displaying a lysogenic cycle do not kill the host and instead become long-term residents as prophages.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Research in 2017 revealed that the bacteriophage Φ3T makes a short viral protein that signals other bacteriophages to lie dormant instead of killing the host bacterium.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Arbitrium is the name given to this protein by the researchers who discovered it.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Given the millions of different phages in the environment, phage genomes come in a variety of forms and sizes.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] RNA phages such as MS2 have the smallest genomes, with only a few kilobases.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] However, some DNA phages such as T4 may have large genomes with hundreds of genes; the size and shape of the capsid varies along with the size of the genome.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The largest bacteriophage genomes reach a size of 735 kb.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Bacteriophage genomes can be highly mosaic, i.e. the genome of many phage species appear to be composed of numerous individual modules.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] These modules may be found in other phage species in different arrangements.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Mycobacteriophages, bacteriophages with mycobacterial hosts, have provided excellent examples of this mosaicism.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] In these mycobacteriophages, genetic assortment may be the result of repeated instances of site-specific recombination and illegitimate recombination (the result of phage genome acquisition of bacterial host genetic sequences).
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Evolutionary mechanisms shaping the genomes of bacterial viruses vary between different families and depend upon the type of the nucleic acid, characteristics of the virion structure, as well as the mode of the viral life cycle.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Some marine roseobacter phages, also known as roseophages, contain deoxyuridine (dU) instead of deoxythymidine (dT) in their genomic DNA.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] There is some evidence that this unusual component is a mechanism to evade bacterial defense mechanisms such as restriction endonucleases and CRISPR/Cas systems which evolved to recognize and cleave sequences within invading phages, thereby inactivating them.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Other phages have long been known to use unusual nucleotides.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] In 1963, Takahashi and Marmur identified a *Bacillus* phage that has dU substituting dT in its genome, and in 1977, Kirnos et al. identified a cyanophage containing 2-aminoadenine (Z) instead of adenine (A).
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The field of systems biology investigates the complex networks of interactions within an organism, usually using computational tools and modeling.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] For example, a phage genome that enters into a bacterial host cell may express hundreds of phage proteins which will affect the expression of numerous host genes or the host's metabolism.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] All of these complex interactions can be described and simulated in computer models.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] For instance, infection of *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* by the temperate phage PaP3 changed the expression of 38% (2160/5633) of its host's genes.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Many of these effects are probably indirect, hence the challenge becomes to identify the direct interactions among bacteria and phage.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Several attempts have been made to map protein–protein interactions among phage and their host.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] For instance, bacteriophage lambda was found to interact with its host, *E. coli*, by dozens of interactions.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Again, the significance of many of these interactions remains unclear, but these studies suggest that there most likely are several key interactions and many indirect interactions whose role remains uncharacterized.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are a major threat to bacteria and prokaryotes, which have evolved numerous mechanisms to block infection (host resistance) or to block the replication of bacteriophages within host cells (anti-phage defense).
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Temperate phages are bacteriophages that integrate their genetic material into the host as extrachromosomal episomes or as a prophage during a lysogenic cycle.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Bacteriophage–host symbiosis may benefit bacteria by providing selective advantages while passively replicating the phage genome.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Metagenomics has allowed the in-water detection of bacteriophages that was not possible previously.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Also, bacteriophages have been used in hydrological tracing and modelling in river systems, especially where surface water and groundwater interactions occur.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The use of phages is preferred to the more conventional dye marker because they are significantly less absorbed when passing through ground waters and they are readily detected at very low concentrations.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Non-polluted water may contain approximately 2×108 bacteriophages per ml.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Bacteriophages are thought to contribute extensively to horizontal gene transfer in natural environments, principally via transduction, but also via transformation.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Metagenomics-based studies also have revealed that viromes from a variety of environments harbor antibiotic-resistance genes, including those that could confer multidrug resistance.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Recent findings have mapped the complex and intertwined arsenal of anti-phage defense tools in environmental bacteria.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Although phages do not infect humans, there are countless phage particles in the human body, given the extensive human microbiome.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] One's phage population has been called the human phageome, including the "healthy gut phageome" (HGP) and the "diseased human phageome" (DHP).
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The active phageome of a healthy human (i.e., actively replicating as opposed to nonreplicating, integrated prophage) has been estimated to comprise dozens to thousands of different viruses.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] There is evidence that bacteriophages and bacteria interact in the human gut microbiome both antagonistically and beneficially.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Preliminary studies have indicated that common bacteriophages are found in 62% of healthy individuals on average, while their prevalence was reduced by 42% and 54% on average in patients with ulcerative colitis (UC) and Crohn's disease (CD).
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Abundance of phages may also decline in the elderly.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] The most common phages in the human intestine, found worldwide, are crAssphages.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] CrAssphages are transmitted from mother to child soon after birth, and there is some evidence suggesting that they may be transmitted locally.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Each person develops their own unique crAssphage clusters.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] CrAss-like phages also may be present in primates besides humans.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] Among the countless phages, only a few have been studied in detail, including some historically important phages that were discovered in the early days of microbial genetics.
[src:bacteriophage/bacteriophage] These, especially the T-phage, helped to discover important principles of gene structure and function.
